What is AOT Compiler?

🧠 First: How Normal Java Runs (Very Simple)

When you write:

System.out.println("Hello");

Step 1 — Compile

javac turns it into bytecode (.class file).

Bytecode is:

(i)Not real machine code
(ii) Not directly understood by CPU
(iii) Meant for the JVM


Step 2 — When Program Starts

Normally Java does this:

a.JVM starts
b.Reads bytecode
c.Runs it slowly using interpreter
d.If some code runs again and again,
e.JVM compiles that part into fast machine code (JIT)

So normal flow is:

Java → Bytecode → JVM → JIT → Machine Code → CPU


🔵 Now What Is AOT?

AOT means:

Compile to machine code BEFORE running the program.

So instead of waiting for JVM to convert it at runtime…

It is converted earlier.

New flow:

Java → Bytecode → Native Machine Code (before running)

When you run the program:

a.It already contains machine code
b.No JIT needed
c.No interpretation
d.Starts immediately


🍽️ Simple Analogy

Normal Java (JIT):

You cook food after the customer orders.
First order is slow. Later it becomes fast.

AOT:

You cook everything before restaurant opens.
Customers get food instantly.

🧠 Why AOT Was Needed?

Because modern apps like:

Microservices
Serverless
Cloud functions

Start and stop quickly.

If JVM takes time to:

Start
Interpret
JIT compile

It wastes time.

So AOT solves:

Slow startup
JIT CPU overhead
🟢 What Happens Internally in AOT?

During build time:

a.All classes are analyzed
b.Methods are compiled to machine code
c.Dependencies are included
d.A native executable file is created

So when you run it:

-It runs directly on CPU
-Like a C or C++ program
-JVM is not needed (in native image case)


⚖️ JIT vs AOT (Super Simple)

JIT	                                                  AOT

Compiles during runtime	                              Compiles before runtime
Slower startup	                                      Faster startup
Better long-term optimization	                      Slightly less smart optimization
Needs JVM running	                                  Can run without JVM


🧠 One-Line Meaning

AOT means your Java program is converted into real machine code before execution,
so it starts faster and doesn’t need runtime compilation.